    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53ee9941b3fefef67175daf212e62d41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 23121,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 57695,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/57695/peter-lawrey",
                "reputation": 535107,
                "display_name": "Peter Lawrey",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 24,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1322513832,
            "creation_date": 1322513832,
            "body": "<p>When you define the array on the definition line, it assumes it know what the type will be so the <code>new int[]<\/code> is redundant.  However when you use assignment it doesn't assume it know the type of the array so you have specify it.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Certainly other languages don't have a problem with this, but in Java the difference is whether you are defining and initialising the fields/variable on the same line.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8302198,
            "question_id": 8302179
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b11ea95357e9daba7e3eb37ebf720c0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 390844,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 751158,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/751158/ziesemer",
                "reputation": 28897,
                "display_name": "ziesemer",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 23,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1322513834,
            "creation_date": 1322513834,
            "body": "<p>Try <code>list = new int[]{4, 5, 6, 7, 8};<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8302199,
            "question_id": 8302179
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zaG25.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 8906759,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6648326,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6648326/masterjoe",
                "reputation": 2390,
                "display_name": "MasterJoe",
                "accept_rate": 71
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1471240468,
            "creation_date": 1471239645,
            "body": "<p>Besides using <code>new Object[]{blah, blah....}<\/code> Here is a slightly shorter approach to do what you want. Use the method below.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static Object [] args(Object... vararg) {\n    Object[] array = new Object[vararg.length];\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; vararg.length; i++) {\n        array[i] = vararg[i];\n    }\n    return array;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>PS - Java is good, but it sucks in situations like these. Try ruby or python for your project if possible &amp; justifiable. (Look <a href=\"http://minborgsjavapot.blogspot.com/2014/12/java-8-initializing-maps-in-smartest-way.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">java 8 still has no shorthand for populating a hashmap<\/a>, and <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/507602/how-can-i-initialise-a-static-map\">it took them so long to make a small change to improve developer productivity<\/a>)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 38949839,
            "question_id": 8302179,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542375
        }
    ],
